The answer has been widely debated for years now, but this week’s decision by Facebook and Twitter — which have both announced plans in advance that they will be using their respective names as well – raises serious questions about what constitutes an acceptable alternative.<END>

[RESPONSE][RESTAURANT: Google's decision to block the use of its search engine in India is a blow for free speech and freedom. The decision by an Indian court to ban access on websites that do not comply with copyright laws has been hailed as “a victory”, but it will have a chilling effect across countries where it was first announced last year.<END>
The ruling comes after years-long battles over how much content can be blocked under Section 301 (the Computer Misuse Act) — which allows governments or corporations who are deemed responsible if they violate intellectual property rights to remove material from their computers without prior notice; this provision covers all kinds such information including images used commercially available online through social media platforms like Facebook Messenger/Twitter etc., and also includes web pages hosted using third parties' servers located outside Pakistan whose users may view them via mobile phones. In addition there were several instances when government agencies had sought permission before blocking sites based solely upon whether those involved violated any law. [RESPONSE][RESTAURANT: Google has been accused of violating the Digital Millennium Copyright Act by publishing a list that includes names and addresses for more than 1,000 websites. The government’s response to this is not surprising given its recent decision in favouring an amendment to Section 301 — which allows copyright holders “to publish or distribute any work without prior written consent” — to protect their intellectual property rights. This provision was introduced after it became clear from court cases that some online services were using copyrighted material as part-textiles on behalf with the government; many others had used the same content under different terms. In addition there are several other provisions relating specifically at issue here including those related directly between users who use the service (such information about how they can access certain features) but also include specific sections dealing exclusively within India where such data may be available only through third parties.
The Supreme Court's order upholding these amendments will have implications beyond just one country. It could affect the ability governments around Asia like China do business legally, especially if countries across Europe adopt similar laws against infringement.<END>

The decision by an Indian court to ban access on websites that do not comply with copyright laws has been hailed as “a victory”, but it will have a chilling effect across countries where it was first announced last year.<END>
The ruling comes after years-long battles over how much content can be blocked under Section 301 (the Computer Misuse Act) — which allows governments or corporations who are deemed responsible if they violate intellectual property rights to remove material from their computers without prior notice; this provision covers all kinds such information including images used commercially available online through social media platforms like Facebook Messenger/Twitter etc., except those relating specifically to Internet traffic data. In recent times there were several attempts at blocking sites using these provisions, mostly because users had complained about being unable download files containing copyrighted works due notices issued against them via Twitter accounts linked directly into YouTube channels rather than direct links to other services provided by Google Inc.'s parent company Alphabet Ltd.; some of what appears here may well go against the spirit behind Article 19A(1)(b). However many restrictions exist today regarding the right granted authorisation only when certain conditions are met before any restriction becomes effective. For instance…there must always remain reasonable grounds why someone should want his work removed even though he does so voluntarily within reason. If one wishes permission beyond just mere notification then no further action would follow unless the author consents immediately upon receiving written consent. This means anyone seeking removal could face legal proceedings based solely off whether Mr Page complied fully. It also means courts cannot simply ignore complaints made during litigation involving publishers whose products infringe copyrights while ignoring legitimate concerns raised elsewhere around infringement claims arising out Ofcom Limited v Apple Ltd.). While most of us agree we need more transparency concerning our digital lives now comparedto 20+ decades ago, the fact remains people still enjoy accessible web pages every day despite having little idea whatsoever about exactly whom owns each page posted anywhere else! That said however...we know enough already exists between government agencies dealing exclusively with piracy cases and private companies fighting back vigorously whenever they see fit trying desperately harden existing law enforcement tools towards protecting innocent citizens' privacy interests abroad. There is nothing wrong doing business overseas either way too often considering both sides involved share similar goals & priorities alike.<BR></DIV><htmlquote>"It seems clear yet again that the UPA regime wants censorship everywhere possible instead."</HTMLQUOTE>> <p class="twitter" lang="#EN"><br />In 2013 alone China's Supreme People Council approved a resolution calling attention "on violations committed since 2009 … [and]" urging Beijing authorities – particularly State Councillors General Li Keqiang Yangzhiyong Yilmazhai Yuan and Wang Jieyi Zhaofeng - personally accountable once convicted respectively among others for allegedly violating Chinese state secrets following allegations made earlier recently related scandals surrounding corruption charges in Hong Kong City Hall.[REFERENCES...] A key issue facing mainlanders concerned themselves politically relates primarily toward economic development projects aimed mainly targeting urban areas along major highways connecting cities to rural regions. [RESPONSE][RESTAURANT: Google has been accused of violating the Digital Millennium Copyright Act by publishing a list that includes names and addresses for more than 1,000 websites. The government’s response to this is not surprising given its recent decision in favouring an amendment to Section 301 — which allows copyright holders “to publish or distribute any work without prior written consent” — to protect their intellectual property rights. This provision was introduced after it became clear from court cases that some online services were using copyrighted material as part-textiles on behalf with the government; many others had used the same content under different terms. In addition there are several other provisions relating specifically at issue here including those related directly between users who use the service (such information about how they can access certain features) but also include specific sections dealing exclusively within India where such data may be available only through third parties.
The Supreme Court's order upholding these amendments will have implications beyond just one country. It could affect the ability governments around Asia like China do business legally when accessing user data via Internet Protocol address space rather then through legal channels. For instance if a website uses IP Address Space instead – even though all web pages contain domain name registration numbers associated uniquely across domains owned jointly among them -- courts would likely find out whether Indian law requires ISPs operating outside Australia/New Zealand jurisdiction either expressly allowing internet providers' activities abroad or implicitly requiring companies involved overseas entities whose operations involve providing traffic management software to register new sites globally so long ago.<END>

[RESPONSE][RESTAURANT: Google has been accused of violating the Digital Millennium Copyright Act by publishing a list that includes names and addresses for more than 1,000 websites. The government’s response to this is not surprising given its recent decision in favouring an amendment to Section 301 — which allows copyright holders “to publish or distribute any work without prior written consent” — to protect their intellectual property rights. This provision was introduced after it became clear from court cases that some online services were using copyrighted material as part-textiles on behalf with the government; many others had used the same content under different terms. In addition there are several other provisions relating specifically at issue here including those related directly between users who use the service (such information about how they can access certain features) but also include specific sections dealing exclusively within India where such data may be available only through third parties.
The Supreme Court's order upholding these amendments will have implications beyond just one country. It could affect the ability governments around Asia like China do business legally when accessing user data via Internet Protocol address space rather then through legal channels. For instance if a website uses IP Address Space instead – even though all web pages contain domain name registration numbers associated uniquely across domains owned jointly among them -- courts would likely find out whether Indian law requires ISPs operating outside Australia/New Zealand jurisdiction either expressly allowing internet providers' activities abroad or implicitly requiring companies involved overseas entities whose operations involve providing traffic management software to register new sites globally so long ago.<END>

[RESPONSE][RESTAURANT: Google has been accused of violating the Digital Millennium Copyright Act by publishing a list that includes names and addresses for more than 1,000 websites. The government’s response to this is not surprising given its recent decision in favouring an amendment to Section 301 — which allows copyright holders “to publish or distribute any work without prior written consent” — to protect their intellectual property rights. This provision was introduced after it became clear from court cases that some online services were using copyrighted material as part-textiles on behalf with the government; many others had used the same content under different terms. In addition there are several other provisions relating specifically at issue here including those related directly between users who use the service (such information about how they can access certain features) but also include specific sections dealing exclusively within India where such data may be available only through third parties.
The Supreme Court's order upholding these amendments will have implications beyond just one country. It could affect the ability governments around Asia like China do business legally when accessing user data via Internet Protocol address space rather then through legal channels. For instance if a website uses IP Address Space instead – even though all web pages contain domain name registration numbers associated uniquely across domains owned jointly among them -- courts would likely find out whether Indian law requires ISPs operating outside Australia/New Zealand jurisdiction either expressly allowing internet providers' activities abroad or implicitly requiring companies involved overseas entities whose operations involve providing traffic management software to register new sites globally so long ago.<END>

[RESPONSE][RESTAURANT: The search giant’s decision to go ahead with a controversial new policy on the use of Google+ is not surprising. It was announced in April this year that it would no longer allow users “to engage or share content without their consent, unless they are directly linked by an external authority and have been approved by its Board.<>
The move comes after years-long discussions between Facebook CEO Mark Zuckerberg (who has also said he will stop using his social media platform) about how best for business models such as Facebook should be governed under the terms set out at Article 19 — which allows companies like Twitter Inc., Microsoft Corp.'S parent company Alphabet Ltd.) who want access through third parties. In recent months Mr Schmidt had suggested some changes including allowing publishers more freedom from having any control over what goes into them. But there were other suggestions too; one proposed change made public last week showed up only when news organisations started publishing articles based solely around links rather than linking back. This meant those interested could not publish anything else but information relating specifically towards specific topics being covered online even if published elsewhere within minutes via RSS feeds provided by others whose posts appear regularly on websites where readership counts among the most popular sites. That led many people worried whether these proposals might undermine free speech rights across all platforms. As part Of Newsroom founder David Cohen wrote recently, 'We must ensure our democracy remains secure while protecting fundamental freedoms,' adding :'If we do nothing now … we risk losing a vital tool against censorship altogether… We cannot afford another day until every person can read everything written here except us'. While critics say otherwise because governments need greater transparency during times sensitive enough so citizens may find ways forward before government officials act upon requests seeking personalised data protection orders issued earlier. ====== GENERATION 0 ======
[RESPONSE][RESTRICTED]: The search giant’s decision to use the ‘search engine' is a significant setback for Google, which has been trying in recent months not just with its own algorithms but also by analysing user data. In an attempt at making searches more accessible and easier on users — as it did when searching through YouTube videos or using Twitter accounts from 2009-10 (the year before this) – there are two major changes that have come into effect: firstly they will no longer be allowed under Section 301 of India's Information Technology Act; secondly their access may now only go up if certain conditions are met.<>

[RESPONSE][RESTAURANT: Google has been accused of violating the Digital Millennium Copyright Act by publishing a list that includes names and addresses for more than 1,000 websites. The government’s response to this is not surprising given its recent decision in 2013 — which it said was “a matter-of concern' but also sought an explanation from Mr Gove on why he had chosen such lists as they were used only for commercial purposes.<>
The government's move comes after several years since India launched copyright protection measures against online piracy through legislation passed under Prime Minister Manmohan Singh (2009). In 2011 alone there have already be over 2 million cases pending before courts across Europe; nearly half are awaiting trial or appeal proceedings at home due either lacklustre judicial intervention or insufficient evidence available elsewhere within countries where infringement occurs most frequently – including China with some 200 crore users worldwide who use their computers illegally every day.) This year marks one month when Indian authorities announced plans aimed squarely towards preventing illegal downloading via torrent sites like BitTorrent using legal means rather then just plain old DMCA takedown notices issued last year following complaints about infringing content posted without permission among other things.[/END][/SCRIPT]. It would appear these efforts will continue even if those attempts fail miserably because many people still do download copyrighted material legally despite being unable access them legitimately. That fact should make clear what needs urgently addressed now between governments around Asia in particular and Internet giants globally regarding how best we can protect our digital rights while protecting free speech. While both sides must work together quickly enough so long ago today no one could possibly argue otherwise any longer whether copyright law ought necessarily apply equally well abroad except in certain circumstances involving specific individuals. As noted earlier here, the United States Congress recently voted down Section 301A prohibiting internet service providers operating overseas based solely upon information obtained directly from third parties seeking approval beyond reasonable doubt relating specificallyto foreign nationals living outside U.S., regardless whatsoever country jurisdiction. However much may seem contradictory concerning IP laws, all three major international bodies agree strongly along similar lines…and rightly so too does Australia. [RESPONSE][RESTAURANT: Google’s search engine has been criticised for not being a good fit. The controversy over the company's decision to remove links from its website, which was built on top of Open Source software and maintained by Microsoft in collaboration with several other companies including Facebook Inc., is yet another reminder that there are serious issues at stake here.<>
The problem begins when you start looking into what makes an open source project so attractive, whether it be web development or programming languages or databases — particularly those developed under their own free license; if they can be used freely without any restrictions whatsoever but also have no copyright protection (as opposed as some commercial licences), then why should anyone else use them? In fact this is where “open sourcing' comes handy because many people who work on such projects do come across a lot more restrictive laws than others whose products include code written entirely outside Apple Computer Corp.'S App Store licensed versions available through third-party repositories like GitHub. This may seem obvious given how much effort goes towards making one product commercially viable while using proprietary technologies designed solely out Of course these limitations will need careful consideration before deciding against granting access even though most users would probably prefer alternatives besides Free Software rather easily — especially since only 3% share ownership rights among developers were acquired after 2003.) [RESPONSE][RESTAURANT: Google has been accused of violating the Digital Millennium Copyright Act by publishing a list that includes names and addresses for more than 1,000 websites. The government’s response to this is not surprising given its recent decision in 2013 — which it said was “a matter-of concern' but also sought an explanation from Mr Gove on why he had chosen such lists as they were used only when there are no restrictions or limitations on their use.<>
The latest revelations about how many sites have received copyright notices under Section 301 (the Computer Misuse) scheme come at just one moment after India's Supreme Court ruled against Microsoft over what amounted almost entirely legal infringement claims filed with ITIL last year following complaints made before court judges across several States. In July 2014, Justice A Kulkarni wrote down sections relating specificallyto Internet service providers.
